This image provided by Airbus shows the 'Flying Honu' turtle-inspired paint job that All Nippon Airways intends to use for its first Airbus A380 superjumbo jet. (Photo: Airbus)
Japanese carrier All Nippon Airways (ANA) will give its first Airbus A380 a giant sea turtle paint job.
ANA placed an order for three A380s in 2016, saying it planned to deploy them on international routes. ANA’s first A380 flight is expected to come in the spring of 2019, when the carrier will launch the aircraft on its route between Tokyo and Honolulu.
ANA’s “Flying Honu” livery comes after nearly 2,200 people submitted entries in a paint-the-plane contest the airline opened to select a unique look for its first A380, the world’s largest passenger jet.
ALSO : AirAsia announces $99 fares for Hawaii, its first-ever U.S. destination (Story continues below)
This image provided by Airbus shows the 'Flying Honu' turtle-inspired paint job that All Nippon Airways intends to use for its first Airbus A380 superjumbo jet. (Photo: Airbus)
ANA first A380 design is released with a nickname "Flying Honu", symbolized good luck, endurance & long life! ⇒ https://t.co/0SPAwvjWyx pic.twitter.com/QS369GByy1
— All Nippon Airways (@FlyANA_official) March 6, 2017 ANA says an “in-house selection committee” chose the design submitted by Chihiro Masuoka of Tokyo, who proposed a concept titled "Sea Turtle Family.”
The Hawaiian green sea turtle – according to ANA – is a symbol of good luck and prosperity in Hawaii. And, the carrier adds, “Honu” is the Hawaiian word for the green sea turtle – hence the “Flying Honu” name for the special paint scheme.
For submitting the winning design, Masuoka wins a pair of round-trip business-class tickets that he can use for ANA’s Tokyo-Honolulu service.
